    "client_msg_id": "771b4182-28fe-4bbf-a146-98f8a08f1fcb",
    "text": "<https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brandolini%27s_law|Brandolini's law> : The amount of energy needed to refute <https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bullshit|bullshit> is an <https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Order_of_magnitude|order of magnitude> bigger than that needed to produce it.\n\nActually a variant on a much older insight: \"_Audacter calumniare, semper aliquid haeret\" (\"_slander boldly, something always sticks\"). Goes back to Francis Bacon at least.",
    "team": "T5TCAFTA9",
    "thread_ts": "1747080701.700389",
    "parent_user_id": "UDCLA1HU4",
    "blocks": [
      {
        "type": "rich_text",
        "block_id": "JME7h",
        "elements": [
          {
            "type": "rich_text_section",
            "elements": [
              {
                "type": "link",
                "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brandolini%27s_law",
                "text": "Brandolini's law"
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": " : The amount of energy needed to refute "
              },
              {
                "type": "link",
                "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bullshit",
                "text": "bullshit"
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": " is an "
              },
              {
                "type": "link",
                "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Order_of_magnitude",
                "text": "order of magnitude"
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": " bigger than that needed to produce it.\n\nActually a variant on a much older insight: \""
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "Audacter calumniare, semper aliquid haeret\" (\"",
                "style": {
                  "italic": true
                }
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "slander boldly, something always sticks\"). Goes back to Francis Bacon at least."
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      }
    ],
